article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 10 of her 19 points in the final four minutes to
lead the Shock to a 74-60 victory over the Washington Mystics on
Friday night.
article.headline: Detroit scores game's final 15 points
article.linkText: Shock pull away from Mystics with late run
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deanna Nolan's second-half heroics are
becoming routine for the Detroit Shock.

Nolan scored 10 of her 19 points in the final four minutes to
lead the Shock to a 74-60 victory over the Washington Mystics on
Friday night.

"That's what she does; she's that good these days," Detroit
coach Bill Laimbeer said. "She did the same thing at Indiana:
scored 17 points in the second half and made all the big shots.

"When her confidence is on, nobody can guard her in this
league."

Detroit closed the game with a 15-0 run, sparked by Nolan's 10
straight points, for its third consecutive victory.

"There were a couple plays called for me at the end and my
teammates found me wide open," Nolan said. "Some loose balls led
to our (players) going and getting them and finding me for
wide-open layups, just like a foot race."

Tamicha Jackson's jumper with 4:42 left gave Washington a 60-59
lead. The Mystics, however, failed to score again and lost their
fourth in a row at home.

"They got some offensive rebounds and then went into a zone,"
said Stacey Dales-Schuman, who scored five points for Washington.

Chamique Holdsclaw, who leads the WNBA in scoring, had 20 points
and 11 rebounds for the Mystics, but declined post-game interviews.

"I have nothing good to say," she said. "Nothing good at
all."

Swin Cash finished with 18 points and seven rebounds for
Detroit.

Ruth Riley's first bucket tied it at 52 for Detroit with 7:40
remaining. She followed with another jumper for another tie and
finished with five points.

Holdsclaw scored the first seven points of the second half for
the Mystics. Coco Miller's jumper gave the Mystics a 52-49 lead
with 8:07 left.

"We played well up until the end and just got outhustled the
last four minutes," Mystics coach Michael Adams said. "Chamique
Holdsclaw is our best player but she can't do it alone."

The first half featured five ties and five lead changes with
neither team leading by more than six points.

Reserve Merlakia Jones gave Detroit a lift by shooting 3-for-3
with a rebound and a block of Holdsclaw during her first seven
minutes.

"We came out for the second half flat, which really bothered me
a bit," Laimbeer said. "But our team is very resilient. When it
comes time to win the game, we always seem to rise to the occasion
and get it done somehow."
